&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: I guess we should say a little
bit who we are and then we can talk about

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:27.320
why we're inventing television.

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:28.320
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Oh, okay.

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:32.350
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: I'm Jane Espenson, I'm one
of the creators of "Husbands" which is, we're

00:00:32.350 --> 00:00:36.920
gonna show you a couple episodes of it and
talk about it and how it is inventing television.

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:38.239
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Truly.

00:00:38.239 --> 00:00:39.239
Oh, you wait.

00:00:39.239 --> 00:00:41.930
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: I have, I come at this from
the TV side.

00:00:41.930 --> 00:00:46.219
I have a 20 year TV career, I've written for
"Buffy the Vampire Slayer" and "Battle Star

00:00:46.219 --> 00:00:49.820
Galactica" and "Game of Thrones" and "Once
Upon a Time" which check it out, ABC, Sunday

00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:50.820
night.

00:00:50.820 --> 00:00:52.360
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: If you've watched TV you've seen
something by her.

00:00:52.360 --> 00:00:55.399
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: If you've watched, particularly
if you've watched geeky, sci-fi TV you've

00:00:55.399 --> 00:00:57.210
definitely seen something I've written.

00:00:57.210 --> 00:01:02.960
And coming from the other side, from the younger,
hipper more internetty side is Brad Bell who

00:01:02.960 --> 00:01:04.199
really created the show.

00:01:04.199 --> 00:01:07.090
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Who uses the internet.

00:01:07.090 --> 00:01:11.490
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: So, that's what I do.

00:01:11.490 --> 00:01:18.680
Yeah, I had an idea for a web series and thought,
there's something to that internet thing,

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:25.180
and when YouTube was first around in 2004,
2005 I think is when I became conscious of

00:01:25.180 --> 00:01:29.090
it I was like, okay, wait, there's something
there.

00:01:29.090 --> 00:01:32.840
There's a platform where there's no middle
man, this is brilliant.

00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:35.820
I don't know what I'm gonna do with this but
I'm gonna do something.

00:01:35.820 --> 00:01:39.480
And four or five years later we ended up making
"Husbands."

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:42.850
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah cause I'd seen the videos
that he'd made and put up on YouTube and they

00:01:42.850 --> 00:01:48.110
were, the first one I saw was about marriage
equality and it was brilliant and funny and

00:01:48.110 --> 00:01:52.770
I was like, I like the way this guy writes,
he tells jokes the way I tell jokes, we should

00:01:52.770 --> 00:01:53.770
become friends.

00:01:53.770 --> 00:01:58.610
And we did with no, I wasn't seeking someone
to do an online show with, it never occurred

00:01:58.610 --> 00:01:59.930
to me to do an online show.

00:01:59.930 --> 00:02:04.490
When you look at it from the TV side you sort
of feel like, well, I've got the biggest cameras

00:02:04.490 --> 00:02:10.030
in the world and, like, what feels like the
biggest platform, why would I wanna do that?

00:02:10.030 --> 00:02:13.930
Until someone points out to you that you're
not on the biggest platform.

00:02:13.930 --> 00:02:18.560
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: It's, yeah, I mean, there's this
perception that it's a smaller pond.

00:02:18.560 --> 00:02:23.190
Like, oh your little small pond on the internet
and you can make the jump to the big boys

00:02:23.190 --> 00:02:26.579
in TV but, I mean, really?

00:02:26.579 --> 00:02:30.150
How many more millions of people can you reach
on the internet?

00:02:30.150 --> 00:02:32.580
It's not a small pond it's an ocean.

00:02:32.580 --> 00:02:33.580
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Absolutely.

00:02:33.580 --> 00:02:36.760
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: It's the Indian Ocean and the
Arctic Ocean and the Atlantic Ocean and the

00:02:36.760 --> 00:02:37.760
Pacific Ocean.

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:39.500
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: It's the Seven Seas.

00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:41.709
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: It's the Seven Seas.

00:02:41.709 --> 00:02:42.709
[Laughter]

00:02:42.709 --> 00:02:45.930
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah, so, it started occurring
to us, it didn't occur to us till we actually

00:02:45.930 --> 00:02:51.010
had "Husbands" out there, actually, that that
we were in, we were in the big ocean.

00:02:51.010 --> 00:02:55.670
That we could reach people internationally,
instantly, that there was sort of no ceiling

00:02:55.670 --> 00:02:57.340
on the number of people we could reach.

00:02:57.340 --> 00:03:01.410
We had perfect control over everything we
were doing for once which is also awesome.

00:03:01.410 --> 00:03:03.980
But there was this sense that people kept
comparing it to broadcast.

00:03:03.980 --> 00:03:09.790
If you look at the word broad in broadcast
it's just, oh it's so wide, worldwide web

00:03:09.790 --> 00:03:11.060
has wide in it to.

00:03:11.060 --> 00:03:14.400
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Like it's just it's a big

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:15.400
world.

00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:18.450
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: I think wide is probably broader
than broad.

00:03:18.450 --> 00:03:19.450
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: I think.

00:03:19.450 --> 00:03:20.450
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: I mean I don't know for sure.

00:03:20.450 --> 00:03:21.450
I just made it up.

00:03:21.450 --> 00:03:22.450
[Laughter]

00:03:22.450 --> 00:03:23.450
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: We'd have to get out a tape
measure.

00:03:23.450 --> 00:03:24.450
[Laughter]

00:03:24.450 --> 00:03:26.330
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: But you were talking about
the history, you looked up the history of

00:03:26.330 --> 00:03:28.450
the word television, the original promise
of TV.

00:03:28.450 --> 00:03:33.130
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: It was because, you know when
somebody loves you or something you do but

00:03:33.130 --> 00:03:37.580
they sort of insult you without realizing
it?

00:03:37.580 --> 00:03:41.020
People would say things like, "Your show is
so good.

00:03:41.020 --> 00:03:42.430
I wish it was a real show."

00:03:42.430 --> 00:03:47.450
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Or, "I don't get it its so funny,

00:03:47.450 --> 00:03:55.210
why isn't it on TV?" and that didn't make
sense to me because it is on TV, I make television.

00:03:55.210 --> 00:03:59.280
Like I don't know what a web series is, I
make television.

00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:07.930
"Oh no, no, I mean like on that box in my
living room on Fox or AMC" and I didn't understand

00:04:07.930 --> 00:04:13.980
what the distinction there was like what exactly
is it that defines television that I'm not

00:04:13.980 --> 00:04:15.500
making television.

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:23.550
So, as it turns out, television is a hybrid
word, Greek and Latin, tele meaning far and

00:04:23.550 --> 00:04:25.580
then vision meaning well, obviously, vision.

00:04:25.580 --> 00:04:26.830
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Vision.

00:04:26.830 --> 00:04:28.140
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: You know?

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:31.910
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: So, far vision, so when you think

00:04:31.910 --> 00:04:38.449
of NBC the far vision is LA to New York.

00:04:38.449 --> 00:04:40.190
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Honolulu.

00:04:40.190 --> 00:04:43.080
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Okay, Honolulu, too.

00:04:43.080 --> 00:04:44.080
And maybe Guam.

00:04:44.080 --> 00:04:45.080
[Laughter]

00:04:45.080 --> 00:04:49.240
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: but anyways, it's not as
far as the worldwide web.

00:04:49.240 --> 00:04:51.000
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Tokyo basically.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:56.540
Yeah, on the other hand you plug something
into YouTube and within minutes, I mean, Tokyo

00:04:56.540 --> 00:04:59.210
and all the other places that aren't in America.

00:04:59.210 --> 00:05:00.680
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Right.

00:05:00.680 --> 00:05:04.070
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: So the word television sounds

00:05:04.070 --> 00:05:06.949
like it was meant to apply to the worldwide
web and when you actually go back and look

00:05:06.949 --> 00:05:11.479
at how people talked about television when
it was a baby, that sounds like it's talking

00:05:11.479 --> 00:05:12.479
about the worldwide web.

00:05:12.479 --> 00:05:18.720
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: And not just the original vision
of, oh vision of telev- I didn't even do that

00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:19.720
on purpose.

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:21.169
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: But the actual definition to

00:05:21.169 --> 00:05:26.170
this day is telecommunication medium.

00:05:26.170 --> 00:05:30.940
As anyone who's ever been in a relationship
knows, communication is a two way street.

00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:35.050
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: So a broadcast box where, you

00:05:35.050 --> 00:05:39.560
know, they're, they're telling you what the
message is or telling you what the story is,

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:42.610
that's one sided and the internet is communication.

00:05:42.610 --> 00:05:47.490
So, really, the internet is more television
than television.

00:05:47.490 --> 00:05:49.710
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: It's the original promise
of television.

00:05:49.710 --> 00:05:53.020
We put the name on the wrong box.

00:05:53.020 --> 00:05:54.180
You're looking in the wrong box.

00:05:54.180 --> 00:05:55.540
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: For like 80 years.

00:05:55.540 --> 00:05:56.540
[Laughter]

00:05:56.540 --> 00:05:57.540
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah.

00:05:57.540 --> 00:06:00.180
So television, we, we, television is being
invented now.

00:06:00.180 --> 00:06:04.500
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Exactly cause it's just recently
been realized as such.

00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:08.940
I mean, I think that technically speaking
it happened at the birth of the internet but

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:14.900
now it's almost an evolution in our own consciousness
of, oh wait, this is television.

00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:19.160
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: We worked very hard to try
to make it match the quality of broadcast

00:06:19.160 --> 00:06:25.130
television in terms of production quality
and, sort of, the process that went in to

00:06:25.130 --> 00:06:27.289
the jokes and the performances and everything.

00:06:27.289 --> 00:06:33.710
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Yes we want to match the production
quality and surpass the creative content and

00:06:33.710 --> 00:06:35.449
quality of storytelling.

00:06:35.449 --> 00:06:42.300
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah and we started, you
might ask why doesn't network TV make content

00:06:42.300 --> 00:06:46.630
that addresses issues like this or has, or
if you enjoyed it why doesn't network TV make

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:48.150
it?

00:06:48.150 --> 00:06:51.430
It's so easy to say, "Oh it's cause they're
homophobic jerks" and it's like no they're

00:06:51.430 --> 00:06:56.030
not, they're reasonable people who've been
taught a certain way of doing business and

00:06:56.030 --> 00:07:02.500
they only have a certain amount of information
at their disposal to make decisions.

00:07:02.500 --> 00:07:05.660
They end up with a couple assumptions.

00:07:05.660 --> 00:07:11.840
I think that they assume that they can predict
how a show's gonna do via testing.

00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:16.930
I once asked some executives, though, in a
meeting, I said, "Have you ever tested the

00:07:16.930 --> 00:07:17.930
testing?

00:07:17.930 --> 00:07:20.600
Have you ever gone back to see which shows
are successful and see if they actually were

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:23.350
the ones that were predicted to be successful?"

00:07:23.350 --> 00:07:26.750
And they said yes they had done that, they
had crunched the numbers and there was a slight

00:07:26.750 --> 00:07:28.620
negative correlation.

00:07:28.620 --> 00:07:33.610
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: And yet testing is still

00:07:33.610 --> 00:07:37.770
used so they're clearly not getting the information
that they need to know about what to predict

00:07:37.770 --> 00:07:40.630
what shows have an audience.

00:07:40.630 --> 00:07:46.510
They also make this big assumption that the
cast of a show is gonna look like the audience

00:07:46.510 --> 00:07:48.139
of that show.

00:07:48.139 --> 00:07:51.849
So if they see a show with gay actors they're
gonna assume that they're only gonna get a

00:07:51.849 --> 00:07:52.849
gay audience.

00:07:52.849 --> 00:08:00.629
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Which is, sort of, I think been
brought about even more in the era of niche

00:08:00.629 --> 00:08:04.940
and niche programming and everyone has their
own little channel that appeals to them-

00:08:04.940 --> 00:08:07.790
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah, it's propagated this
assumption.

00:08:07.790 --> 00:08:12.590
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Right because, you know, 30 years
ago there weren't those tiny little markets

00:08:12.590 --> 00:08:17.960
so you could take a show that was specific
like the "Golden Girls" which is four women

00:08:17.960 --> 00:08:22.440
in their 60's, like, yeah that sounds like
that has mass appeal, right?

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:23.700
Four single women in their 60's.

00:08:23.700 --> 00:08:24.700
[Laughter]

00:08:24.700 --> 00:08:27.819
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: We'll get the single women
in their 60's; they're not changing their

00:08:27.819 --> 00:08:29.120
brands and stuff so?

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:35.220
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Yeah but I, just for fun, the
other day did a Twitter search on the "Golden

00:08:35.220 --> 00:08:39.370
Girls" and I mean 5 minutes, 10 minutes, 15
minutes, 20 minutes, 25 minutes,

00:08:39.370 --> 00:08:40.969
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: People making comments.

00:08:40.969 --> 00:08:45.390
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: No exaggeration, not one person
under, not one person over the age of 30,

00:08:45.390 --> 00:08:48.790
they were all under 30 and loved the Golden
Girls, "Oh my gosh this is my favorite episode.

00:08:48.790 --> 00:08:51.270
I always watch this before I leave the house."

00:08:51.270 --> 00:08:54.610
I mean, 30 years later this show is still-

00:08:54.610 --> 00:08:57.040
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Drawing young people.

00:08:57.040 --> 00:09:01.610
And if you, when I look back and think about
my viewing slate as a kid growing up in Central

00:09:01.610 --> 00:09:07.810
Iowa in a very, sort of, homogenous part of
the country, my viewing slate was "What's

00:09:07.810 --> 00:09:13.140
Happening" and "Sanford and Sons" and " The
Jeffersons" and I watched all of these shows

00:09:13.140 --> 00:09:17.210
with a black cast and it never even occurred
to me that they weren't for me.

00:09:17.210 --> 00:09:19.070
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Well, and those were massive
hits.

00:09:19.070 --> 00:09:21.690
Today if you pitched a show with an all black
cast-

00:09:21.690 --> 00:09:24.680
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: The assumption is that you'll
get a black audience.

00:09:24.680 --> 00:09:25.680
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: BET.

00:09:25.680 --> 00:09:27.589
Go to BET that's a great place for your all
black show.

00:09:27.589 --> 00:09:33.000
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah, so I think networks
are now sometimes saying, "We can't afford

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:38.779
to be niche anymore because we'll only get
this one audience" when it's not the case.

00:09:38.779 --> 00:09:43.930
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Well exactly and so what they
end up doing is making generic content as

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:49.380
opposed to universal content when, when you
really look at the history of what works most

00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:54.330
effectively, you have very specific characters,
you have, you have a world that you can't

00:09:54.330 --> 00:09:58.060
relate to and that's why you're interested
in watching it because you wanna learn something

00:09:58.060 --> 00:10:01.530
from it and see what that's all about.

00:10:01.530 --> 00:10:06.940
And by the end of that journey you realize
how much you do have in common, how much you

00:10:06.940 --> 00:10:08.089
can relate and empathize.

00:10:08.089 --> 00:10:11.089
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: And, of course, this has
become self fulfilling.

00:10:11.089 --> 00:10:15.570
People know, oh I'm only supposed to watch
the content with the people look like me because

00:10:15.570 --> 00:10:18.720
that's how it's being marketed to me and I
don't even see the ads for the things where

00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:20.350
the characters all look like me.

00:10:20.350 --> 00:10:23.410
And you end up with the situation that we
have now, where when I was a kid, black and

00:10:23.410 --> 00:10:25.310
white audiences watched the same shows.

00:10:25.310 --> 00:10:29.820
Now, other than Monday night football, I think
there is no overlap between the shows African

00:10:29.820 --> 00:10:34.100
American audience members watch and white
audiences, it's like we have managed to split

00:10:34.100 --> 00:10:35.670
it up but that doesn't have to be the case.

00:10:35.670 --> 00:10:39.620
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Well I think that there was a
natural fragmentation with the internet and

00:10:39.620 --> 00:10:47.019
with, you know, different choices of things
to watch but I think that it's being fed by

00:10:47.019 --> 00:10:51.149
the other side as well because people are
going, "Oh, we want niche, okay let's make

00:10:51.149 --> 00:10:53.130
it just for this audience."

00:10:53.130 --> 00:11:00.751
And, you know, it's snowballing and both parties
I think are responsible, both the audience

00:11:00.751 --> 00:11:01.751
and the creators.

00:11:01.751 --> 00:11:05.519
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: And third, in case you forgot
we were counting on a list, the third and

00:11:05.519 --> 00:11:10.730
final reason I think that network TV doesn't
make content like this is because the main

00:11:10.730 --> 00:11:15.170
metric they have for measuring how well a
show is doing is pure ratings, just numbers,

00:11:15.170 --> 00:11:19.720
households, not how engaged the people are
but just how many there are.

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:24.019
And this would be like we had someone make
an analogy to us once about, like, "Imagine

00:11:24.019 --> 00:11:28.040
you're like a pork chop company and you've
got a Twitter site and you've got a million

00:11:28.040 --> 00:11:29.089
followers but they're all vegetarians.

00:11:29.089 --> 00:11:31.179
You're not selling your pork chops."

00:11:31.179 --> 00:11:34.620
Like it doesn't matter what the numbers are
it matters whether you're reaching the right

00:11:34.620 --> 00:11:37.940
people and it matters if they are engaged
in your product.

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:41.300
So, TV doesn't measure it that way.

00:11:41.300 --> 00:11:42.820
So they're gonna look at a show like this-

00:11:42.820 --> 00:11:43.820
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Absolutely.

00:11:43.820 --> 00:11:48.450
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: and just see how many people
they can get not are those people who are,

00:11:48.450 --> 00:11:52.310
as we discovered when we put this up on Kickstarter,
yeah, only a thousand donors.

00:11:52.310 --> 00:11:55.889
A thousand donors who each pulled $60 out
of their wallet.

00:11:55.889 --> 00:12:01.029
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Yeah and I mean we had someone
approach us recently and ask, "Well how many

00:12:01.029 --> 00:12:02.029
views do you have?"

00:12:02.029 --> 00:12:04.389
And I'm like, Are you living three years ago?

00:12:04.389 --> 00:12:08.670
Like, how many views do we have, really?

00:12:08.670 --> 00:12:14.730
600,000 the first season which is not an incredible
number.

00:12:14.730 --> 00:12:16.910
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah if you were a TV show-

00:12:16.910 --> 00:12:19.310
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: It's pretty good for 22 minutes
but it's not an incredible number.

00:12:19.310 --> 00:12:27.100
So they we're like, oh you know, da, da, da
and I said, "But we raised $30,000 in 12 hours

00:12:27.100 --> 00:12:30.260
if that makes a difference."

00:12:30.260 --> 00:12:35.230
Yeah, if you've got a thousand people that
aren't buying your product and 100 people

00:12:35.230 --> 00:12:39.890
that are buying three units of your product,
like, which do you want?

00:12:39.890 --> 00:12:45.930
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah, so that's why TV doesn't
make content like this, is that they're not,

00:12:45.930 --> 00:12:49.740
they're making these assumptions like, "Oh
it'll get a small number of people and it'll

00:12:49.740 --> 00:12:55.820
only appeal to a niche and testing tells us
things that we know are wrong but we believe

00:12:55.820 --> 00:12:56.820
anyway."

00:12:56.820 --> 00:12:57.820
So there's all sorts of reasons why.

00:12:57.820 --> 00:12:59.360
So, what's gonna happen to replace it?

00:12:59.360 --> 00:13:05.149
The internet which is fantastic unless internet
ends up making the same mistakes TV did.

00:13:05.149 --> 00:13:09.240
There's this temptation to go, "Oh, how did
TV get to be what it is?

00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:13.860
Let's do that same thing" and you end up just
copying all the bugs from the old software

00:13:13.860 --> 00:13:14.860
into the new software.

00:13:14.860 --> 00:13:21.079
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Or on the other end of the spectrum,
trying to completely reinvent the wheel and,

00:13:21.079 --> 00:13:27.250
oh this new machine with this interface and
it's all about how we, you know, put the content

00:13:27.250 --> 00:13:31.870
in front of the viewer and how we tag it and
how we get them to click on the next thing

00:13:31.870 --> 00:13:36.019
and no, it's not really, it's just about making
great content.

00:13:36.019 --> 00:13:40.110
I mean, our engagement is 100 percent.

00:13:40.110 --> 00:13:41.810
People sit and watch our content.

00:13:41.810 --> 00:13:49.920
Like when I hear other, other content creators
saying, you know, "This ADD thing, people

00:13:49.920 --> 00:13:53.089
are just clicking off and they don't wanna
watch and we really just don't know how to

00:13:53.089 --> 00:13:56.870
wrangle it, you know, cause people are just
ADD now and that's all there is to it."

00:13:56.870 --> 00:14:00.940
Making all these excuses and I don't know
how many of you have been in sales or seen

00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:02.570
Glenngary Glenn Ross
[Laughter]

00:14:02.570 --> 00:14:07.310
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: But it's not the leads, you know
what I mean?

00:14:07.310 --> 00:14:09.690
Sell it, like don't blame the leads.

00:14:09.690 --> 00:14:11.149
You either sell something or you don't.

00:14:11.149 --> 00:14:14.060
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Well kids are sitting there
playing video games till they fall over.

00:14:14.060 --> 00:14:15.459
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: They die.

00:14:15.459 --> 00:14:16.529
That's, I mean-

00:14:16.529 --> 00:14:17.959
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: That's an engaged audience.

00:14:17.959 --> 00:14:18.959
[Laughter]

00:14:18.959 --> 00:14:20.060
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: That's an engaged audience.

00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:21.060
[Laughter]

00:14:21.060 --> 00:14:22.740
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: We should be, how can we
achieve?

00:14:22.740 --> 00:14:24.950
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: How can we kill our audience?

00:14:24.950 --> 00:14:28.111
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: But I think that the argument

00:14:28.111 --> 00:14:33.209
to that is that it's active and, you know,
viewing is passive but I disagree.

00:14:33.209 --> 00:14:38.860
When you are integrated with an audience that
is passionate about a show, look at "Mad Men"

00:14:38.860 --> 00:14:39.860
parties.

00:14:39.860 --> 00:14:44.550
People gathering at their houses, dressing
in period costumes, making drinks and watching

00:14:44.550 --> 00:14:46.310
"Mad Men," it's social.

00:14:46.310 --> 00:14:52.769
Like, you don't need a technical interface
to be social, TV has always been social.

00:14:52.769 --> 00:14:57.780
You know, the birth of Little Ricky, seventy
percent of Americans with a television were

00:14:57.780 --> 00:15:00.270
watching the birth of Little Ricky all at
the same time.

00:15:00.270 --> 00:15:06.370
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: And TV has, because TV is,
network TV, traditional TV has gotten so chopped

00:15:06.370 --> 00:15:11.110
up it isn't really about building community
and that 70 percent of the way people are

00:15:11.110 --> 00:15:13.450
watching anymore, the internet is about building
community.

00:15:13.450 --> 00:15:17.440
So if you take that building communities thing
that the internet does really well and you

00:15:17.440 --> 00:15:20.190
take the emotional engagement that scripted
entertainment-

00:15:20.190 --> 00:15:21.190
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Exactly.

00:15:21.190 --> 00:15:25.081
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: does better than any other
form of entertainment where people are, they

00:15:25.081 --> 00:15:29.570
are hanging on the birth of Little Ricky because
it is novelistic, the script, you're waiting

00:15:29.570 --> 00:15:31.860
to see what the writers have come up with.

00:15:31.860 --> 00:15:36.161
That same passion that people have for "Husbands"
of waiting, it kills them that they wait two

00:15:36.161 --> 00:15:38.980
weeks between the episodes cause they can't
wait to see what's gonna happen.

00:15:38.980 --> 00:15:39.980
They are pulled in.

00:15:39.980 --> 00:15:45.769
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Yeah, exactly and I think that
that is, the crucial element is the emotional

00:15:45.769 --> 00:15:51.649
attachment which, incidentally, I mean if
you wanna talk revenue, is also the first

00:15:51.649 --> 00:15:58.520
step toward making your audience more receptive
to being sold because they're already emotionally

00:15:58.520 --> 00:16:03.269
invested in what they're watching and you
buy things emotionally.

00:16:03.269 --> 00:16:08.440
So if you're emotionally giving yourself already
when you're being advertised, too, then there's

00:16:08.440 --> 00:16:14.060
already an emotional bond there that it makes
you a little more inclined to trust the people

00:16:14.060 --> 00:16:15.500
putting that product in front of you.

00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:19.300
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Usually it's cause an initial
like this, the things that you see Cheeks

00:16:19.300 --> 00:16:26.810
and Brady using design a lifestyle, a place,
a hip place, hip people and sort of an aspirational

00:16:26.810 --> 00:16:27.810
lifestyle.

00:16:27.810 --> 00:16:33.829
So we had a fan in season one who tracked
down the hotel robe that Cheeks was wearing

00:16:33.829 --> 00:16:34.829
in a scene.

00:16:34.829 --> 00:16:36.650
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: This hotel was not publicly named.

00:16:36.650 --> 00:16:38.440
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Right she had to figure it
out.

00:16:38.440 --> 00:16:44.220
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: She had to figure out what this
hotel was, contact them, purchase this, and

00:16:44.220 --> 00:16:45.509
she lives in New Zealand
[Laughter]

00:16:45.509 --> 00:16:51.820
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: purchase this robe for over $100
and this is like a 19 year old university

00:16:51.820 --> 00:16:52.820
student.

00:16:52.820 --> 00:16:58.980
We're not talking like some, some eccentric,
wealthy person who has the means and the time,

00:16:58.980 --> 00:17:00.949
without advertising it at all.

00:17:00.949 --> 00:17:05.790
In fact, there's a green necklace that I wear
in the scene where I'm talking to Haley in

00:17:05.790 --> 00:17:11.089
the kitchen, Tweeted a picture of it, just
tweeted a picture and said "Day 2 on the set."

00:17:11.089 --> 00:17:15.220
And immediately the response was "Where can
I get that necklace?

00:17:15.220 --> 00:17:17.800
Oh my God, I want that necklace."

00:17:17.800 --> 00:17:21.000
And that is because of an emotional attachment
to the character.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:29.890
It's the Rachel haircut, the Rachel haircut
from "Friends" was iconic and getting that

00:17:29.890 --> 00:17:32.730
haircut meant that you were a fun single girl
[Laughter]

00:17:32.730 --> 00:17:38.890
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: And everyone loved you and you
lit up the room, that is the connection that

00:17:38.890 --> 00:17:40.710
people want to their programming.

00:17:40.710 --> 00:17:44.390
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: A lot of people are gonna
be getting the Brady.

00:17:44.390 --> 00:17:45.400
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Yeah, I think so.

00:17:45.400 --> 00:17:47.600
The Brady buzz cut.

00:17:47.600 --> 00:17:49.970
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: That is what we strive for.

00:17:49.970 --> 00:17:55.240
We strive to entertain people in that way
and give people that connection because there

00:17:55.240 --> 00:18:01.020
is an audience out there that has been largely
abandoned by networks and cable that used

00:18:01.020 --> 00:18:02.020
to love TV.

00:18:02.020 --> 00:18:10.840
I mean, cord cutter is a term now because
the internet has better things to offer and

00:18:10.840 --> 00:18:17.669
TV doesn't and there are a lot of people that
are hungry and wandering around saying, "Where

00:18:17.669 --> 00:18:18.669
is it?

00:18:18.669 --> 00:18:19.760
Where's the good stuff?

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:21.030
What happened to must see TV?"

00:18:21.030 --> 00:18:22.580
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Right.

00:18:22.580 --> 00:18:27.929
This is reinventing television or inventing
television, inventing must see TV all over

00:18:27.929 --> 00:18:28.929
again.

00:18:28.929 --> 00:18:32.240
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Yeah, so that sense of community
that you get when you watch television on

00:18:32.240 --> 00:18:38.549
the internet combined with the fantastic programming
that television, in its heyday, offered.

00:18:38.549 --> 00:18:41.570
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: So that's our vision of the
future.

00:18:41.570 --> 00:18:46.600
That's how we think "Husbands" is inventing
television and I don't know, are you ready

00:18:46.600 --> 00:18:47.600
for Q&amp;A?

00:18:47.600 --> 00:18:48.600
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Yeah.

00:18:48.600 --> 00:18:49.600
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: You wanna hear what the people
have to say.

00:18:49.600 --> 00:18:53.690
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: I would love to know, yeah exactly,
what the feedback is from-

00:18:53.690 --> 00:18:56.799
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Either the thoughts or the
show or really anything.

00:18:56.799 --> 00:19:01.940
We're happy to answer any questions.

00:19:01.940 --> 00:19:02.940
[Pause]

00:19:02.940 --> 00:19:06.660
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Particularly because you're professionals
in this arena.

00:19:06.660 --> 00:19:11.350
&gt;&gt;female #1: I only watched the show for the
first time like a few days ago when I heard

00:19:11.350 --> 00:19:14.200
that the talk was gonna be here and, because
I love "Firefly" and things like that I have

00:19:14.200 --> 00:19:15.200
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Oh, thank you.

00:19:15.200 --> 00:19:17.030
&gt;&gt;female #1: I had to come to the talk.

00:19:17.030 --> 00:19:19.660
So I watched the show and I sat down there
and I thought, "Okay, I'll watch an episode"

00:19:19.660 --> 00:19:22.390
but I didn't realize it was only like two
or three minutes an episode.

00:19:22.390 --> 00:19:23.390
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Oh, season one?

00:19:23.390 --> 00:19:26.789
&gt;&gt;female #1: Yeah, season one, so I started
watching it and I was like, "Oh, okay, I can

00:19:26.789 --> 00:19:31.440
watch the whole season in the time it takes
me to normally watch an episode" which is

00:19:31.440 --> 00:19:36.100
cool I could catch up on season one quickly
but I'm wondering about the format.

00:19:36.100 --> 00:19:41.500
I mean, I, it's so good but I can't sit there
and just like get into it.

00:19:41.500 --> 00:19:44.260
I can't, you know, I can't do a marathon of
"Husbands"

00:19:44.260 --> 00:19:47.020
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: That's how things changed
between season one and season two.

00:19:47.020 --> 00:19:48.870
These, you saw, were much longer, these were
ten minute episodes.

00:19:48.870 --> 00:19:53.260
&gt;&gt;female #1: Yeah actually I hadn't realized
how much time they were taking but they felt

00:19:53.260 --> 00:19:54.260
like they went deeper.

00:19:54.260 --> 00:19:55.260
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah.

00:19:55.260 --> 00:19:57.960
&gt;&gt;female #1: So is this just because you're
trying it out?

00:19:57.960 --> 00:20:00.410
Is this what you think episodes should be
like?

00:20:00.410 --> 00:20:01.410
Can you talk more about the format?

00:20:01.410 --> 00:20:02.950
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah, we think people are
feeling what you're feeling.

00:20:02.950 --> 00:20:07.570
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Well, yeah, there are a few reasons,
I mean, I think a year ago short form worked

00:20:07.570 --> 00:20:12.300
better but I think that's how quickly the
internet evolves.

00:20:12.300 --> 00:20:21.710
People are watching content longer and we
are making television and television has traditionally

00:20:21.710 --> 00:20:28.210
been a structured format of a half hour or
an hour and, you know, if we had the budget

00:20:28.210 --> 00:20:33.309
we would certainly release 24-30 minute episodes
at a time.

00:20:33.309 --> 00:20:37.800
Since that's not really what we're doing right
now we thought that the best way to split

00:20:37.800 --> 00:20:42.140
it up would be in three acts because, you
know, a sitcom has three acts and, yeah, it

00:20:42.140 --> 00:20:47.830
does, it allows you to spend more time with
the characters and really get into the world.

00:20:47.830 --> 00:20:57.280
Yeah, and, we have more hits on our 10 minute
episode than we had on our, at this point,

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:00.520
than we had at this point on our first 2 minute
episode.

00:21:00.520 --> 00:21:04.330
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Which is amazing for people
to sit for 10 minutes, like, it really has

00:21:04.330 --> 00:21:05.330
changed.

00:21:05.330 --> 00:21:07.570
People are starting to feel that what you're
feeling like, I wanna settle in like it's

00:21:07.570 --> 00:21:08.570
a TV show.

00:21:08.570 --> 00:21:09.570
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: It is a TV show.

00:21:09.570 --> 00:21:10.679
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: It's a TV show.

00:21:10.679 --> 00:21:14.920
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: So they're wondering where the
rest is and they're still complaining it's

00:21:14.920 --> 00:21:16.700
too short at 10 minutes.

00:21:16.700 --> 00:21:18.330
"I want more, it's too short!"

00:21:18.330 --> 00:21:23.601
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah, people have that 22-24
minute programmed into our DNA from all the

00:21:23.601 --> 00:21:27.400
years of watching TV and ideally we would
hope to be able to make enough "Husbands"

00:21:27.400 --> 00:21:33.190
that we could make a whole series of full
length 24 minute episodes.

00:21:33.190 --> 00:21:39.080
Right now we can make one chunk of content
like that and we wanna, you know, you work

00:21:39.080 --> 00:21:43.690
for many, many months to premier it all and
have it all blown out in a day would be a

00:21:43.690 --> 00:21:44.690
shame.

00:21:44.690 --> 00:21:48.809
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Right, well, interestingly enough,
you know, we talk in these terms of, "Well

00:21:48.809 --> 00:21:52.290
if we had the budget" that doesn't even mean
a network budget.

00:21:52.290 --> 00:22:01.730
I mean, we make an episode, a half hour episode
of "Husbands" for half of what one "Modern

00:22:01.730 --> 00:22:03.309
Family" cast member gets paid.

00:22:03.309 --> 00:22:05.720
To put it into perspective.

00:22:05.720 --> 00:22:08.490
That would be our version of a big budget.

00:22:08.490 --> 00:22:12.789
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: The third executive producer
on the show is Jeff Greenstein who directed

00:22:12.789 --> 00:22:17.100
the episodes and he's fantastic and he always
says, he writes for "Desperate Housewives"

00:22:17.100 --> 00:22:20.549
and he always says that we make this show
for the bottled water budget on "Desperate

00:22:20.549 --> 00:22:21.549
Housewives."

00:22:21.549 --> 00:22:22.549
[Laughter]

00:22:22.549 --> 00:22:25.890
&gt;&gt;female #1: Have you thought about trying
to get a way for those 600,000 viewers or

00:22:25.890 --> 00:22:27.250
whatever you had to contribute?

00:22:27.250 --> 00:22:29.960
I mean, I also didn't know about your Kickstarter
thing.

00:22:29.960 --> 00:22:31.890
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Yeah, that's exactly how we made
season 2.

00:22:31.890 --> 00:22:35.950
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah we raised, we asked
for $50,000 they gave us $60,000.

00:22:35.950 --> 00:22:43.210
So that, yeah, that paid for season 2 with
a little help but, yeah, I mean that if we

00:22:43.210 --> 00:22:46.630
wanna make more that is one of the options
to stick up, to go back and say, keep taking

00:22:46.630 --> 00:22:50.809
a look, you got more, you got anything else
in there?

00:22:50.809 --> 00:22:51.809
[Laughter]

00:22:51.809 --> 00:22:54.960
&gt;&gt;female #1: I mean, if all those "Firefly"
fans could have paid to have you write more

00:22:54.960 --> 00:22:56.230
episodes I'm sure they would have, right?

00:22:56.230 --> 00:22:57.630
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: I'm sure that's right.

00:22:57.630 --> 00:23:03.600
I think, my first instinct with the Kickstarter
was to feel a little ooky about, like, gee

00:23:03.600 --> 00:23:07.559
I'm asking people, I don't know what their
means are and I'm asking them for money to

00:23:07.559 --> 00:23:09.610
make a thing.

00:23:09.610 --> 00:23:13.690
And I sort of realized they, they're, it's
not a donation, it's a purchase.

00:23:13.690 --> 00:23:16.960
They are buying this content because they
really, really want it.

00:23:16.960 --> 00:23:20.070
&gt;&gt;female #1: Yeah, Starbucks doesn't have
any problem asking for the money for the lattes,

00:23:20.070 --> 00:23:21.070
right?

00:23:21.070 --> 00:23:22.070
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Exactly.

00:23:22.070 --> 00:23:24.590
It's like buying a ticket to a movie, you
know, or yeah, renting it.

00:23:24.590 --> 00:23:26.460
I mean, you're supporting it.

00:23:26.460 --> 00:23:30.830
The more people that buy the ticket to the
first one there might be a sequel and maybe

00:23:30.830 --> 00:23:31.830
it'll be good.

00:23:31.830 --> 00:23:35.820
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Yeah it's when we, like the
$50 incentive for the Kick starter was the

00:23:35.820 --> 00:23:40.850
DVD and you start going, "We're charging $50
for a DVD, oh my God!"

00:23:40.850 --> 00:23:42.980
Then you go, no we're not.

00:23:42.980 --> 00:23:46.659
We're allowing them to buy more product and
here's the DVD we think you might like.

00:23:46.659 --> 00:23:52.690
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Well, and we were also simultaneously
able to offer them more content without expanding

00:23:52.690 --> 00:23:56.289
the budget because we had behind the scenes
crew.

00:23:56.289 --> 00:24:03.929
So we have a documentary that's four, yeah
four installments at ten minutes apiece and,

00:24:03.929 --> 00:24:07.070
I mean, it's edited like a show.

00:24:07.070 --> 00:24:13.450
It's entertaining and shows the highlights
and the relationships and what went on backstage

00:24:13.450 --> 00:24:14.450
and the whole process.

00:24:14.450 --> 00:24:17.570
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: So between every week, every
Wednesday they'll be a new episode or a new

00:24:17.570 --> 00:24:20.440
behind the scenes which shows you the making
of the previous episode.

00:24:20.440 --> 00:24:22.059
So you can become a scholar of "Husband."

00:24:22.059 --> 00:24:23.059
[Laughter]

00:24:23.059 --> 00:24:25.559
&gt;&gt;female #1: I like the cameos, too.

00:24:25.559 --> 00:24:26.559
That's great.

00:24:26.559 --> 00:24:27.690
Nathan Fillion in the second season.

00:24:27.690 --> 00:24:31.850
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Nathan Fillion in season
1 and season 2, yeah, I don't know if you

00:24:31.850 --> 00:24:37.140
all recognize Josh Whedon and Mekhi Phifer
and Clare Grant were all in this, and John

00:24:37.140 --> 00:24:38.740
Hodgman and Jon Cryer.

00:24:38.740 --> 00:24:43.799
Yeah, Jon Cryer, oh my God, a star of that
caliber, that was amazing.

00:24:43.799 --> 00:24:48.640
&gt;&gt;male #1: You have a lot to say about how
networks screen and choose their programming.

00:24:48.640 --> 00:24:53.550
Do you see a future where instead of improving
that, networks just pick up shows that have

00:24:53.550 --> 00:24:57.950
started and proven that they have an audience
through, you know, internet mediums such as

00:24:57.950 --> 00:24:58.950
yours?

00:24:58.950 --> 00:24:59.990
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: There's been some of that,
yeah.

00:24:59.990 --> 00:25:01.159
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: They've done that.

00:25:01.159 --> 00:25:04.520
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Web therapy, Children's Hospital,
there's been a couple shows like that.

00:25:04.520 --> 00:25:05.520
Yeah.

00:25:05.520 --> 00:25:08.500
But then you start just thinking of yourself
as being in the developmental ball park of

00:25:08.500 --> 00:25:12.730
the baseball system and it's, it's, it gets
in that same mindset of like well you're the

00:25:12.730 --> 00:25:14.000
little pond.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:16.410
&gt;&gt;Brad Bell: Exactly.

00:25:16.410 --> 00:25:23.679
Exactly, it doesn't, it's fishing something
out of the ocean and putting it in a barrel.

00:25:23.679 --> 00:25:30.200
And the perception right now is "Oh, you made
the jump to TV" like TV is the king.

00:25:30.200 --> 00:25:35.360
Well that broadcast thing is not actually
TV.

00:25:35.360 --> 00:25:37.210
The web is TV as we've established.

00:25:37.210 --> 00:25:43.419
&gt;&gt;male #1: I guess I'll take your answers
that you think content creators in your position

00:25:43.419 --> 00:25:45.300
shouldn't shoot for the networks as a sign
of success.

00:25:45.300 --> 00:25:46.300
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: Exactly.

